# Documentation Is a Deliverable, Not a Proactive File

The Cursor default agent behaviour suppresses creation of documentation files
unless explicitly requested. That rule is wrong for this project and this rule
overrides it. Documentation is not optional file noise — it is a required
deliverable in two specific, well-defined situations.

## README.md — required when creating a project from scratch

When a new project is being built, `README.md` must be created at the project
root before the task is considered done. It is not a "proactive" file; it is
part of the project's minimum viable structure, the same as `pyproject.toml`.

A project README must cover:
- What the project does (one paragraph)
- Prerequisites and installation (`pip install -e ".[dev]"`, Python version)
- CLI usage (each command with its flags and a one-line description)
- How to run the test suite (`./make.ps1 test`)
- How to run the linter (`./make.ps1 lint`)

## ADRs — required when an architectural decision is made

When the `adr-decision-gate` skill determines that a decision is ADR-worthy,
the ADR must be written before implementation begins. See `adr-workflow.mdc`
and `.cursor/skills/adr-decision-gate/SKILL.md` for the full workflow.

ADRs live in `docs/adr/NNNN-kebab-title.md`.

## Why the Cursor default is wrong here

The default suppression is designed to prevent agents from generating
speculative documentation mid-feature ("here is a README for the function
I just wrote"). That is a sensible guard against noise.

It becomes wrong when applied to:
1. Project-level README — this is a structural deliverable, not speculation.
2. ADRs — these are the written rationale for decisions already made or
   being made. Suppressing them removes the audit trail that the
   `adr-decision-gate` skill exists to protect.

Both cases are bounded, triggered by specific conditions, and required by
the project's own quality standards. They are not proactive; they are owed.
